{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517851"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12841"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.01,0.05,0.86]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52772"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5284"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1049"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15408"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52772"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. He has passed very little urine during this time and has been experiencing severe muscle cramps. One week ago, he was started on bortezomib, thalidomide and dexamethasone for recently diagnosed multiple myeloma. This diagnosis was made after a presentation with hypercalcaemia, acute kidney injury, anaemia and unexplained rib fractures. He initially seemed to respond well to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, hypertension, heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (EF 40%) and type 2 diabetes mellitus. He does not take any regular medications other than his recently prescribed chemotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 144/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. He is alert with dry mucous membranes. His jugular venous pressure is not raised. His heart sounds are dual and his chest is clear with a prolonged expiratory phase. He has pitting oedema to above his knees. While examining the patient, he begins to show signs of shortness of breath and dizziness. An ECG demonstrates ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 6.2 mmol/L (3.6-5.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate 2.4 mmol/L (1.0-1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 140 mmol/L (136-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUric acid 485 \u00b5mol/L (208\u2013428)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 1.6 mmol/L (2.0-2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addison\u0027s disease","Progression of multiple myeloma","Septic shock","Heart failure exacerbation","Tumour lysis syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Etumour lysis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. He has recently been diagnosed with multiple myeloma and likely had a high tumour burden. As a consequence of the chemotherapy destroying a large number of tumour cells, intracellular contents are being released into the blood, explaining his hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, and hyperuricaemia. The hypocalcaemia is due to the phosphate binding to free calcium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgression of multiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E may explain some of the signs and symptoms listed, such as the nausea, pitting oedema (which could indicate acute kidney injury) and hyperuricaemia. However, as the patient was placed on treatment relatively soon after diagnosis, this option is less likely. Furthermore, in patients with worsening multiple myeloma symptoms, hypercalcaemia would be expected - however, this patient presents with hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile this patient does have a prior diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eheart failure\u003C/strong\u003E and there are potential signs of an exacerbation such as his pitting oedema, a heart failure exacerbation does not explain his electrolyte imbalance, particularly the hyperphosphataemia and hyperuricaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea. However, septic shock would not explain his electrolyte imbalance. Furthermore, in septic shock, the patient would be expected to have hypotension, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E (primary adrenal insufficiency) is a cause of hyperkalaemia and can present with nausea, vomiting, and tachycardia. However, patients with Addison\u0027s disease are more likely to have hyponatraemia and hypotension, which are not present here. Additionally, Addison\u0027s disease would not explain the hyperphosphataemia and hyperuricaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s muscle cramping is likely due to hypocalcaemia, and the ventricular tachycardia is most likely due to hyperkalaemia. These findings, along with the characteristic electrolyte abnormalities shortly after initiating chemotherapy for a high-burden malignancy, strongly support the diagnosis of tumour lysis syndrome. This condition is an oncological emergency requiring prompt recognition and management to prevent further complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour lysis syndrome is an oncological emergency characterised by hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hyperuricaemia, and hypocalcaemia.","Tumour lysis syndrome typically occurs after initiation of chemotherapy in patients with high tumour burden.","ECG changes and arrhythmias in tumour lysis syndrome are often due to hyperkalaemia."],"references":["Howard SC, Jones DP, Pui CH. The tumor lysis syndrome. N Engl J Med. 2011 May 12;364(19):1844-54. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMra0904569","Adeyinka A, Bashir K. Tumor Lysis Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518985/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T19:44:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T19:46:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5284"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52772"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"